{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a1aea8b0-b8f5-4e41-a75e-0fede0747fa8","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates these:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Open with any text editor.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files appear in `/cores/`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — For recent crash info:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourApp\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries without any extra setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cb344d9b-91a4-4d57-b02f-e9b96365fe4f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"7653:834FC:D9A3C7:100CF0B:69FE9218"},"id":"ef83963e-279e-41b6-ad43-eb437c977667","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:47:12.039Z","parentId":"e9b09e0e-8895-4c3b-bf04-772903a193e1"}
